Organization = {{European Space Agcy; Ctr Remote Imaging Sensing \& Proc; Natl Univ
   Singapore; Reg Inst Environm Technol; CNES; Arianespace; ESCAP;
   SpotImage Spot Asia}},
Abstract = {{A two-hectare plot of a deciduous dipterocarp-oak forest of Doi
   Suthep-Pui National Park of northern Thailand protected against fire for
   28 years was compared with a similar, but frequently burnt forest nearby
   with respect to changes in tree phenology. The twin objectives of the
   study were to find out the effects of forest fire protection on tree
   phenology using Crown Density Method (CDM) and identify the potential
   uses of satellite images in monitoring tree phenology. Study area was
   identified and located with the help of satellite images (SPOT, Landsat,
   and ERS) and global positioning satellite (GPS). To survey the tree
   communities, six meter wide transects with a total length of 650 m in
   each site were laid out across the slope of the mountain following a
   bearing of 60 degrees. The seasonal variation in leafing, flowering and
   fruiting of trees was monitored over the period of eight months from May
   to December 1996, using crown density method.
   The mean community scores for senescent leaves in November and December
   were significantly higher in the burnt area, than in the protected area.
   Shorea siamensis var. siamensis and Craibiodendron stellatum (Pierre)
   W.W. Sm. retained their leaves longer in the dry season or early rainy
   season in the protected area than in the burnt area. Trees in the burnt
   area had less fruit in May than in the Protected area, even if their
   flowering scores were comparatively higher. Leafing phenologies of
   certain species were greatly altered. Burning seemed to affect the
   fruiting capacity of some of the trees. Overall, this study shows that
   fire protection is a useful conservation management tool in deciduous
   dipterocarp forest for changing tree phenologies toward more favorable
   conditions for wild animals.
   The weak and strong points behind using CDM are given. Potential uses of
   Satellite Images in monitoring tree phenology are described in terms of
   cost, reliability and availability of the space data.}},
