   SAF}},
Title = {{Interactions of fire and defoliating insects in western forests: Some
   multi-century patterns}},
Booktitle = {{PROCEEDINGS OF THE 1996 SOCIETY OF AMERICAN FORESTERS CONVENTION:
   DIVERSE FORESTS, ABUNDANT OPPORTUNITIES, AND EVOLVING REALITIES}},
Year = {{1996}},
Pages = {{222-227}},
Note = {{1996 National Convention of the Society-of-American-Foresters,
   ALBUQUERQUE, NM, NOV 09-13, 1996}},
Organization = {{Soc Amer Foresters}},
Abstract = {{We examined historical records and used dendrochronology to determine
   long-term landscape patterns of forests, fire. and defoliator outbreaks.
   Historical descriptions suggest that old growth ponderosa pine forests
   and light, frequent fires were more common in the 19(th) century.
   Dendrochronology indicated that defoliating insect outbreaks occurred at
   fairly regular intervals from 1750 to 1900. In the 20(th) century,
   outbreaks have occurred more frequently. We hypothesize that fire
   control and heavy logging of pine since about 1910 have altered tree
   species distribution resulting in more-favored habitat for defoliating
   insects. Recent outbreaks have occurred over larger areas and cause more
   tree mortality. Recent forest fires in these outbreak areas rapidly
   developed into conflagrations. Defoliator/fire episodes are becoming
   more difficult to predict and control. There are abundant opportunities
   for research and innovative management practices to reverse the current
   trend.}},
